# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-3221
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "3D animation"@en ;
  curric:slug "3d-animation" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover how to create 3D animations using
  industry-standard software. They will gain a greater understanding of how 3D animation is
  used to make the media products that we consume. They will explore the basics of
  modelling, texturing, animating to create 3D models."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having previously created and manipulated 2D vector images, pupils are now
  ready to explore how these skills translate into three dimensions. This unit introduces the
  fundamentals of 3D modelling and animation, showing how shapes, textures and movement combine
  to create realistic digital worlds. By working with tools used by professionals, pupils
  develop an understanding of how complex animations are built. Learning this now helps them
  appreciate the creative and technical processes behind modern media, preparing them to take
  on more ambitious digital projects with confidence and precision.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3221-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3221-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3221-3 ;
  curric:id "3221"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.888078Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3206
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Clear messaging in digital media"@en ;
  curric:slug "clear-messaging-in-digital-media" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will use a range of skills across several pieces of software.
  They will work between applications to create a poster and slides on a given theme. The
  unit is designed so that pupils can apply skills that they may have previously learnt as
  well as those learnt in the unit."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils move from primary to secondary school, this unit supports their
  transition by building on digital skills developed in KS2. It helps them use the school
  network safely and respectfully while working across multiple applications. By creating a
  poster and presentation, pupils learn to combine text and images to communicate ideas clearly
  - skills they will apply across subjects throughout secondary school.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3206-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3206-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3206-3 ;
  curric:id "3206"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.890317Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3214
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Developing vector graphics"@en ;
  curric:slug "developing-vector-graphics" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will design graphics using vector graphic editing software.
  They will apply their skills by creating an illustration, a logo, and icons. Pupils will
  recognise that objects and be grouped and combined to create new elements and that vector
  drawings are made up of paths."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having previously been introduced to vector graphics, pupils now deepen
  their understanding of how to create precise, scalable digital artwork. Building on earlier
  work with objects, layers and grouping, this unit develops pupils’ ability to design and
  refine complex graphics with accuracy and control. Learning these skills prepares pupils to
  consider how clear and professional visuals are essential for communicating ideas effectively
  across any context.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3214-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3214-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3214-3 ;
  curric:id "3214"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.049680Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3209
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using fundamental programming constructs in a block-based language"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-fundamental-programming-constructs-in-a-block-based-language" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will build their confidence and knowledge of the key
  programming constructs (sequence, iteration, selection and variables). Learners will use
  Scratch to explore the key programming constructs firstly through editing pre-existing
  code and then by developing their own programs."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit reintroduces block-based programming to establish a shared
  foundation, allowing teachers to identify and address gaps in knowledge. It reinforces the
  key programming constructs: sequence, variables, selection, and count-controlled iteration.
  By securing these essentials now, pupils are better prepared for more complex programming in
  future units, including the transition from block-based to text-based languages later in KS3.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3209-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3209-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3209-3 ;
  curric:id "3209"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.130871Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3222
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using data science"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-data-science" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover how to use data to investigate problems and make
  changes to the world around them. Pupils will be exposed to both global and local data
  sets and gain an understanding of how visualising data can help with the process of
  identifying patterns and trends."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils encounter more data in their daily lives, it is important they
  understand how it can be used to answer questions and drive meaningful change. This unit
  introduces the principles of data science, showing pupils how systematic approaches can
  reveal patterns and insights that might otherwise be missed. By exploring how data informs
  decisions within their school community, pupils see the value of evidence-based thinking and
  develop the critical skills needed to interpret information thoughtfully and responsibly.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3222-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3222-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3222-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3222-4 ;
  curric:id "3222"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.226878Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information ,
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development .

oakcurric:unit-3219
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Introduction to Python programming"@en ;
  curric:slug "introduction-to-python-programming" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to text-based programming with Python. Pupils start
  with programs involving input and output, and gradually move on to using arithmetic
  operations, randomness, selection, and iteration. Pupils will consolidate these skills in
  a project at the end of the unit."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having built confidence with key programming constructs through
  block-based programming, pupils are now ready to apply these skills in a text-based language.
  This shift helps them understand how the same principles of sequence, selection, iteration,
  and variables are expressed in a different environment, developing their precision and
  problem-solving. Learning this now prepares pupils to take on more complex challenges, such
  as processing and analysing data stored in structures, which they will explore in later
  units.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3219-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3219-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3219-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3219-4 ;
  curric:id "3219"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.417085Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3210
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Physical computing using the micro:bit"@en ;
  curric:slug "physical-computing-using-the-micro-bit" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will plan, develop, and evaluate a physical computing
  project. They will break down the project into smaller, easier-to-solve tasks. They will
  put these plans into action to create a working prototype that they use to evaluate their
  successes and identify future improvements."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already explored the core programming constructs of sequence,
  selection and iteration, pupils are now ready to apply these skills to real-world contexts
  through physical computing. This unit shows them that programming isn’t limited to on-screen
  outputs, helping them understand how code can control devices in the physical world. Pupils
  also develop their approach to project work by planning, implementing and reviewing solutions
  which are techniques that are valuable across subjects and essential for tackling more
  complex computing challenges in the future.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3210-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3210-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3210-3 ;
  curric:id "3210"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.493798Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3218
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Mobile app development"@en ;
  curric:slug "mobile-app-development" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit takes pupils from designer to developer in order to create their own
  mobile app. Using App Lab from code.org, learners will familiarise themselves with the
  coding environment and have an opportunity to build on the programming concepts they used
  in previous units to undertake a project."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils’ programming skills develop, they are ready to take on a more
  ambitious project that brings together the key constructs they have previously learned. This
  unit introduces a new block-based environment, giving pupils the chance to apply their
  knowledge of sequence, selection, iteration, and variables in a fresh context. By designing
  and building a mobile app, they experience the full process of planning, problem-solving and
  refining their work, showing them how programming can be used to create practical, real-world
  solutions.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3218-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3218-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3218-3 ;
  curric:id "3218"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.580983Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development .

oakcurric:unit-3211
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Data modelling"@en ;
  curric:slug "data-modelling" ;
  rdfs:comment """By the end of this unit pupils should be able to model data within a spreadsheet.
  Pupils will progress from using basic formulas to using inbuilt functions. Pupils will
  apply sorting and searching techniques to data and explore how conditional formatting can
  be used to present data effectively."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their understanding of variables from programming, pupils now
  apply this concept to organising and processing data in spreadsheets. This unit helps them
  see how raw data can be structured and transformed into meaningful information, allowing them
  to model real-life situations and draw conclusions. These skills are essential for future
  computing work and are widely used in subjects such as maths, science and geography, as well
  as in everyday tasks where data analysis supports decision-making.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3211-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3211-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3211-3 ;
  curric:id "3211"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.638987Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3216
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Developing for the Web"@en ;
  curric:slug "developing-for-the-web" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will explore the technologies that make up the internet and
  WWW. Starting with an exploration of the building blocks of the WWW, HTML, and CSS. They
  will construct a fully functioning website and discover how websites are catalogued for
  effective retrieval by search engines."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils become more independent digital learners, it is important that
  they understand how the web works, not just how to use it. This unit introduces the building
  blocks of websites, HTML and CSS, helping pupils see how content is created and structured.
  By making their own website, they grow in confidence as digital creators while also learning
  how search engines organise and retrieve information. These skills strengthen
  problem-solving, creativity and digital literacy, supporting future learning across subjects.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3216-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3216-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3216-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3216-4 ;
  curric:id "3216"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.870992Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3215
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Computer systems and data science"@en ;
  curric:slug "computer-systems-and-data-science" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore the layers of computer systems from programs to
  the physical components that store and execute these programs. They will discover the
  fundamental binary building blocks that make up computer systems and how systems are
  evolving for developments such as AI."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils’ use of technology becomes more advanced, it is important they
  understand how computer systems work and how different components interact. This unit takes
  pupils beyond simply using technology to exploring its underlying structure, from programs to
  operating systems. By comparing traditional computing systems with those that use artificial
  intelligence, pupils gain insights into the technologies shaping their world and develop the
  critical thinking needed to understand and question how these systems affect their daily
  lives and future learning.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3215-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3215-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3215-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3215-4 ;
  curric:id "3215"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.892011Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-computing-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology ,
    oakcurric:thread-artificial-intelligence .

oakcurric:unit-3217
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Data representation: text and numbers"@en ;
  curric:slug "data-representation-text-and-numbers" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will be introduced to binary digits and how they can be used
  to represent text and numbers. Pupils will perform conversions between binary and decimal
  numbers and how binary can be used to represent characters. They will explore how
  cryptography can be used to protect data."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """At this stage, pupils are ready to move beyond simply using technology to
  understanding how it works at its core. Binary underpins everything a computer does, from
  processing text and numbers to storing data. By comparing it with the familiar decimal
  system, pupils can begin to see how computers represent information differently from humans.
  Learning about binary now gives pupils the insight to make sense of everyday technology, such
  as file sizes measured in kilobytes, megabytes and gigabytes, helping them become more
  informed and confident users of digital systems.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3217-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3217-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3217-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3217-4 ;
  curric:id "3217"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.921406Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3225
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Machine learning using the micro:bit"@en ;
  curric:slug "machine-learning-using-the-micro-bit" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit is designed to develop pupils programming skills in a new engaging
  context: physical computing, using the BBC micro:bit. They will get acquainted with the
  host of components built into the micro:bit, and write simple programs that use these
  components to interact with the physical world."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Applying programming skills to a physical computing context deepens
  pupils’ understanding of how code influences the world around them. This approach develops
  essential problem-solving, logical thinking and creative skills, helping pupils to see
  programming as more than just on-screen activity. By connecting their code to real, tangible
  outcomes, pupils gain a clearer sense of technology’s impact and begin to appreciate its role
  in shaping everyday life in an increasingly digital society.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3225-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3225-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3225-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3225-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3225-5 ;
  curric:id "3225"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.925316Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-computing-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-artificial-intelligence .

oakcurric:unit-3220
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Python programming with sequences of data"@en ;
  curric:slug "python-programming-with-sequences-of-data" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover how data is represented and processed in
  sequences, such as lists and strings. They will cover a spectrum of operations on
  sequences of data, that range from accessing an individual element to manipulating the
  entire sequence though real world practical activites."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already written Python programs that handle input, output,
  calculations and control flow, pupils are now ready to explore how data can be stored and
  processed in sequences such as strings and lists. This unit develops their understanding of
  how to work with collections of data, moving from accessing individual elements to
  manipulating entire sets. Learning these techniques at this stage helps pupils see how
  structured data makes programs more efficient, preparing them to solve increasingly complex
  problems where handling and organising information is essential.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3220-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3220-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3220-3 ;
  curric:id "3220"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.927148Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3223
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Data representation: images and sound"@en ;
  curric:slug "data-representation-images-and-sound" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will focus on digital media such as images and sounds, and
  discover the binary digits that lie beneath these types of media. They will explore how
  images and sound can be manipulated and consider the link between quality of images and
  sound and the resulting file size."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils’ understanding of binary develops, they are ready to explore how
  it underpins the digital media they use every day. This unit helps them see that images and
  sound are not just files on a screen but are made up of binary digits that represent visual
  and audio data. By uncovering the hidden structure behind digital media, pupils gain a deeper
  appreciation of how technology works and why quality, size and format matter. This knowledge
  supports more informed and creative use of digital tools as they move on to complex media
  projects.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3223-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3223-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3223-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3223-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3223-5 ;
  curric:id "3223"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.130102Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3207
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Computer networks and data transmission"@en ;
  curric:slug "computer-networks-and-data-transmission" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore the impact networks have on our daily lives. They
  will define what a network is and explore the benefits of networking, before covering how
  data is transmitted across networks using protocols. They will investigate different types
  of network and hardware required."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils begin secondary school, they are using the internet and
  connected devices more independently and in increasingly complex ways. At this stage, it is
  important that they understand what is happening behind the scenes when data is shared or
  services are accessed online. This unit builds a foundation for making informed decisions
  about privacy and security, helping pupils see how network design and data transmission
  affect their experience. Learning this now equips them to navigate technology critically and
  responsibly as its role in their lives expands.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3207-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3207-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3207-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3207-4 ;
  curric:id "3207"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.678548Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-networks .

oakcurric:unit-3224
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Introduction to cybersecurity"@en ;
  curric:slug "introduction-to-cybersecurity" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit takes pupils on a journey of discovery about techniques used by
  cybercriminals to steal data, disrupt systems and infiltrate networks. They will consider
  the value of data to organisations and what it is used for. They will look at social
  engineering techniques and common cybercrimes."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils grow older and begin using a wider range of digital tools, they
  increasingly interact with networks that connect across the world. This unit develops their
  understanding of online threats, moving beyond the basic risks they have encountered so far.
  Pupils learn about the scale of these threats at individual, organisational and governmental
  levels and, crucially, the steps they can take to protect themselves and their data. This
  empowers them to act safely and responsibly, both in their personal lives and in future work
  settings where secure practices are essential.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3224-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3224-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3224-3 ;
  curric:id "3224"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.689628Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-networks ,
    oakcurric:thread-safety-and-security .

oakcurric:unit-3208
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using media to gain support for a cause"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-media-to-gain-support-for-a-cause" ;
  rdfs:comment """During this unit, pupils develop their understanding of information technology and
  digital literacy skills. They will use the skills learnt across the unit to create a blog
  post about a real-world cause that they would like to gain support for."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils become more independent in their use of technology, they need to
  understand how digital media shapes opinions and decisions. This unit helps them develop the
  skills to judge the reliability of online sources and understand copyright and licensing,
  preparing them to use content safely and ethically. By creating a blog to promote a cause,
  pupils practise communicating clearly and persuasively. These skills will be built on across
  subjects when presenting arguments, analysing sources and sharing ideas responsibly.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3208-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3208-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3208-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3208-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3208-5 ;
  curric:id "3208"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.775595Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

